%md

## HW11.0:  Broadcast versus Caching in Spark

#### 11.0.1: What is the difference between broadcasting and caching data in Spark? Give an example (in the context of machine learning) of each mechanism (at a highlevel). Feel free to cut and paste code examples from the lectures to support your answer.

Spark allows intermediate results to be cached in memory, which can be helpful if there are data that need to be used multiple times. On the other hand, broadcast variables are cached _locally on each machine_, so that we don't have to include copies of the data with every task.

HW11.0: Broadcast versus Caching in Spark

11.0.1: What is the difference between broadcasting and caching data in Spark? Give an example (in the context of machine learning) of each mechanism (at a highlevel). Feel free to cut and paste code examples from the lectures to support your answer.

Spark allows intermediate results to be cached in memory, which can be helpful if there are data that need to be used multiple times. On the other hand, broadcast variables are cached locally on each machine, so that we don't have to include copies of the data with every task.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

#############################
# Example of caching

testRDD = sc.parallelize([1, 2, 3]).cache()

print "Collect a cached RDD"
print testRDD.collect()

# Now testRDD has been cached, and we can use this data structure without needing to go back and parallelizing it every time it is called


#############################
# Example of broadcasting

i = 4
broadVar = sc.broadcast(i)

print "\nPrint a broadcast variable"
print broadVar.value

# Now all tasks have access to broadVar

%md
#### 11.0.2: Review the following [Spark-notebook-based implementation of KMeans](http://nbviewer.ipython.org/urls/dl.dropbox.com/s/41q9lgyqhy8ed5g/EM-Kmeans.ipynb) and use the broadcast pattern to make this implementation more efficient. Please describe your changes in English first, implement, comment your code and highlight your changes.

We can utilize the broadcast pattern to broadcast our model to the tasks. When we calculate the new centroids, instead of setting the "centroids" variable equal to the "centroids_new" variable, we can just broadcast the new centroids.

%pyspark # We need this to be able to show matplotlib plots inline instead of in a window import matplotlib matplotlib.use('Agg') import matplotlib.pyplot as plt import numpy as np import StringIO def showMPL(plot): img = StringIO.StringIO() plot.savefig(img, format='svg') img.seek(0) print "%html
" + img.buf + "
"

%pyspark

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from math import sqrt
import json

size1 = size2 = size3 = 1000
samples1 = np.random.multivariate_normal([4, 0], [[1, 0],[0, 1]], size1)
data = samples1
samples2 = np.random.multivariate_normal([6, 6], [[1, 0],[0, 1]], size2)
data = np.append(data,samples2, axis=0)
samples3 = np.random.multivariate_normal([0, 4], [[1, 0],[0, 1]], size3)
data = np.append(data,samples3, axis=0)

# Randomlize data
data = data[np.random.permutation(size1+size2+size3),]
np.savetxt('data/HW11/data.csv',data,delimiter = ' ', fmt='%.10f')

%pyspark

def plot_samples(title, means):
    
    plt.clf()
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10/3*2))
    
    # Plot axis
    plt.axhline(0, color='black', alpha=0.1)
    plt.axvline(0, color='black', alpha=0.1)
    
    # Plot data points
    plt.scatter(samples1[:, 0], samples1[:, 1], color='#4ECDC4', alpha=0.5)
    plt.scatter(samples2[:, 0], samples2[:, 1], color='#C7F464', alpha=0.5)
    plt.scatter(samples3[:, 0], samples3[:, 1], color='#FF6B6B', alpha=0.5)
    
    # Plot centroids
    plt.scatter(means[0][0], means[0][1], marker='*', s=100, color='white', edgecolor='black')
    plt.scatter(means[1][0], means[1][1], marker='*', s=100, color='white', edgecolor='black')
    plt.scatter(means[2][0], means[2][1], marker='*', s=100, color='white', edgecolor='black')
    
    # Annotate centroids
    for i in means:
        text = '({:.2f}'.format(i[0]) + ', ' + '{:.2f})'.format(i[1])
        plt.annotate(text, 
            xy = i, xytext = (20, -20),
            textcoords = 'offset points', ha = 'left', va = 'top',
            bbox = dict(boxstyle = 'round,pad=0.5', fc = 'white', alpha = 0.5),
            arrowprops = dict(arrowstyle = '->', connectionstyle = 'arc3,rad=0'))
    
    # Label graph
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel('x')
    plt.ylabel('y')
    showMPL(plt)


plot_samples('Data with true centroids', [[0,4],[6,6],[4,0]])

%pyspark

# When k-means iterations are done, plot the path
def plot_iterations(allIterations):
    
    plt.clf()
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10/3*2))
    
    centroidPaths = np.array(allIterations)
    
    allSamples = np.array(samples1)
    allSamples = np.append(allSamples, samples2, axis=0)
    allSamples = np.append(allSamples, samples3, axis=0)
    
    clusterSize = samples1.shape[0]
    
    colors = ['#4ECDC4', '#C7F464', '#FF6B6B']
    
    # Plot axis
    plt.axhline(0, color='black', alpha=0.1)
    plt.axvline(0, color='black', alpha=0.1)
    
    # Plot each cluster
    for i in range(3):
        plt.scatter(allSamples[(i * clusterSize):((i+1) * clusterSize), 0], allSamples[(i * clusterSize):((i+1) * clusterSize), 1], 
                    color=colors[i], alpha=0.5, zorder=1)
        plt.plot(centroidPaths[:,i,0], centroidPaths[:,i,1], color='grey', alpha=0.9,
                 marker='o', markersize=5, markerfacecolor='white', markeredgecolor='black', zorder=2)
        plt.scatter(centroidPaths[-1,i,0], centroidPaths[-1,i,1], marker='*', s=150, 
                    color='white', edgecolor='black', zorder=3)
        
        finalCentroid = centroidPaths[-1, i]
        text = '({:.2f}'.format(finalCentroid[0]) + ', ' + '{:.2f})'.format(finalCentroid[1])
        plt.annotate(text, 
            xy = finalCentroid, xytext = (20, -20),
            textcoords = 'offset points', ha = 'left', va = 'top',
            bbox = dict(boxstyle = 'round,pad=0.5', fc = 'white', alpha = 0.5),
            arrowprops = dict(arrowstyle = '->', connectionstyle = 'arc3,rad=0'))

    # Label graph
    plt.title('Samples 1, 2, and 3 with iterated centroid estimates')
    plt.xlabel('x')
    plt.ylabel('y')
    showMPL(plt)

%pyspark

# Calculate which class each data point belongs to
def nearest_centroid(line):
    x = np.array([float(f) for f in line.split(' ')])
    closest_centroid_idx = np.sum((x - bCentroids.value)**2, axis=1).argmin() # This is changed from original to use bCentroids.value
    return (closest_centroid_idx,(x,1))

# Calculate the within set sum of squared error (WSSSE)
def calcError(line):
    center = bCentroids.value[nearest_centroid(line)[0]]
    point = np.array([float(f) for f in line.split(' ')])
    return sqrt(sum([x**2 for x in (point - center)]))

# Function to iterate k-means algorithm
def runKMeans(K, inputFile, iterations):
    global bCentroids  # This is changed from original to use bCentroids
    
    # Initialization: initialization of parameter is fixed to show an example
    centroids = np.array([[0.0,0.0],[2.0,2.0],[0.0,7.0]])
    
    # Broadcast these centroids to all tasks
    bCentroids = sc.broadcast(centroids)  # This is changed from original to broadcast the centroids variable
    
    iter_centroids = []
    iter_centroids.append(centroids)
    iteration = 0
    
    D = sc.textFile(inputFile).cache()
    
    print '{:12s}{:<20s}{:<20s}{:<20s}'.format('Iteration', 'Centroid 1', 'Centroid 2', 'Centroid 3')
    print '----------------------------------------------------------------------'
    rowPrint = '{:<12d}({: 6.4f}, {: 6.4f})  ({: 6.4f}, {: 6.4f})  ({: 6.4f}, {: 6.4f})  '.format
    print rowPrint(iteration,
                   centroids[0][0], centroids[0][1],
                   centroids[1][0], centroids[1][1],
                   centroids[2][0], centroids[2][1])
    
    for i in range(iterations):
            
        res = D.map(nearest_centroid).reduceByKey(lambda x,y : (x[0] + y[0], x[1] + y[1])).collect()
        res = sorted(res, key = lambda x : x[0])  # sort based on clusted ID
        centroids_new = np.array([x[1][0]/x[1][1] for x in res])  # divide by cluster size
        iter_centroids.append(centroids_new)
        
        if np.sum(np.absolute(centroids_new - bCentroids.value)) < 0.01:
            break

        bCentroids = sc.broadcast(centroids_new) # Instead of setting centroids = centroids_new, we just broadcast centroids_new
        iteration += 1

        print rowPrint(iteration,
               centroids_new[0][0], centroids_new[0][1],
               centroids_new[1][0], centroids_new[1][1],
               centroids_new[2][0], centroids_new[2][1])
        
    WSSSE = D.map(calcError).reduce(lambda x, y: x + y)
    print '\nWSSSE =', WSSSE
    
    return iter_centroids

%pyspark

allIterations = runKMeans(3, 'data/HW11/data.csv', 10)

%pyspark

plot_iterations(allIterations)

# HW11.1:  Loss Functions

#### 11.1.1: In the context of binary classification problems, does the linear SVM learning algorithm yield the same result as a L2 penalized logistic regression learning algorithm? In your reponse, please discuss the loss functions, and the learnt models, and separating surfaces between the two classes.

The two learning algorithms might not yield the same result. SVM uses hinge loss, while logistic regression with L2 uses log loss. The two loss functions (among others) can be visualized using the below graph. Logistic regression fits the data as if they were along a continuous sigmoid function, where the separating surface occurs where the probability of one class is greater than 0.5 (usually). SVM fits a hyperplane that attempts to separate the data into two classes that lie in either side of the hyperplane, with a margin of 1 on either side of the hyperplane. It can be seen from the hinge loss function that even a guess on the correct side of the hyperplane will be penalized if it is between 0 and 1.

![loss functions](http://scikit-learn.org/stable/_images/plot_sgd_loss_functions_001.png)

#### 11.1.2: In the context of binary classification problems, does the linear SVM learning algorithm yield the same result as a perceptron learning algorithm?

The two learning algorithms might not yield the same result. In general, the perceptron does not attempt to maximize the margin between the two classes, while the SVM does via the hinge loss function. The perceptron loss function is similar to the hinge loss function, except there is no penalty for a correct guess, regardless of the distance from the separating hyperplane (hinge loss penalizes a correct guess that is closer than 1 to the hyperplane).

# HW11.2 Gradient descent

#### 11.2.1: In the context of logistic regression describe and define three flavors of penalized loss functions.  Are these all supported in Spark MLLib (include online references to support your answers)?

The three types of regularization are ordinary least squares (which actually doesn't use any regularization), ridge (L2 regularization) and lasso (L1 regularization). All three are supported in Spark MLLib, and the documentation can be found [here](http://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/mllib-linear-methods.html#linear-least-squares-lasso-and-ridge-regression).

#### 11.2.2: Describe probabilitic interpretations of the L1 and L2 priors for penalized logistic regression (HINT: see synchronous slides for week 11 for details)

The L2 norm can be descibed as the Euclidean distance, while the L1 norm can be described as the Manhattan distance. Probabilistically speaking, L1 can be interpreted using a Laplacian probability density function, whereas L2 can be interpreted using a Gaussian probability density function.

11.3.1: Generate 2 sets of linearly separable data with 100 data points each using the data generation code provided below and plot each in separate plots. Call one the training set and the other the testing set.

11.3.2: Modify this data generation code to generating non-linearly separable training and testing datasets (with approximately 10% of the data falling on the wrong side of the separating hyperplane. Plot the resulting datasets.

%pyspark

from numpy.random import rand, random

def generateData(n, seperable=True):
    """ 
    generates a 2D linearly separable dataset with n samples. 
    The third element of the sample is the label
    """
    xb = (rand(n)*2-1)/2-0.5
    yb = (rand(n)*2-1)/2+0.5
    xr = (rand(n)*2-1)/2+0.5
    yr = (rand(n)*2-1)/2-0.5
    inputs = []
    for i in range(len(xb)):
        if not seperable:
            randomNum1 = random()
            randomNum2 = random()
            if randomNum1 < 0.1:
                inputs.append([-xb[i],-yb[i],1])
            else:
                inputs.append([xb[i],yb[i],1])
            if randomNum2 < 0.2:
                inputs.append([-xr[i],-yr[i],-1])
            else:
                inputs.append([xr[i],yr[i],-1])
        else:
            inputs.append([xb[i],yb[i],1])
            inputs.append([xr[i],yr[i],-1])
                
    return inputs

%pyspark

def showData(train, test):
    colorDict = {1.0: '#0099ff', -1.0: '#ff5050'}
    trainColors = [colorDict[train[x, 2]] for x in range(len(train))]
    testColors = [colorDict[train[x, 2]] for x in range(len(test))]
    
    plt.clf()
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10/3*2))
    
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.scatter(train[:,0], train[:,1], c=trainColors, edgecolors=trainColors)
    plt.title("Training data")
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.scatter(test[:,0], test[:,1], c=testColors, edgecolors=testColors)
    plt.title("Testing data")
    showMPL(plt)

%pyspark

# Linearly seperable data

train = np.array(generateData(100))
test = np.array(generateData(100))
showData(train, test)

%pyspark

from pyspark.mllib.regression import LabeledPoint
from pyspark.mllib.classification import LogisticRegressionWithSGD

# Load and parse the data
def parsePoint(line):
    if line[2] == -1: cat = 0
    if line[2] == 1: cat = 1
    return LabeledPoint(cat, line[:2])
    
trainData = sc.parallelize(train).map(parsePoint).cache()
testData = sc.parallelize(test).map(parsePoint).cache()

%pyspark

def LogRegMLLib(iter):
    # Build the model
    model = LogisticRegressionWithSGD.train(trainData, iterations=iter, regType='l1', intercept=True)
    
    # Evaluating the model on testing data
    predictions = testData.map(lambda p: (p.label, model.predict(p.features)))
    accuracy = predictions.filter(lambda (l, p): l == p).count() / float(testData.count())
    print "Iterations:", iter
    print "Model:", model
    print "Accuracy:", str(accuracy)
    print "\n"
    return accuracy
    
iterations = [1, 5, 10, 50, 100, 500, 1000]
accuracies = []

for i in iterations:
    accuracies.append(LogRegMLLib(i))

%pyspark

from collections import namedtuple

Point = namedtuple('Point', 'x y w')

def readPoint(line):
    x = [float(i) for i in line[:2]]
    x.append(1.0)  #bias term
    return Point(x, float(line[2]), sqrt(sum([i ** 2 for i in x])))
    
trainData = sc.parallelize(train).map(readPoint).cache()
testData = sc.parallelize(test).map(readPoint).cache()

%pyspark

def WeightedLogRegLasso(train, learningRate=0.05, iterations=10, regParam=0.01, convThreshold=0.01):
    n = train.count()
    featureLen = len(train.take(1)[0].x)
    
    wIterations = []
    
    # Initialize weights to random
    w = sc.broadcast(np.random.normal(size=featureLen))
    wIterations.append(w.value)
    
    # Print header
    print '{:15s}{:15s}{:15s}{:15s}'.format('iteration', 'weight[0]', 'weight[1]', 'bias')
    print '-'*60
    iterPrint = '{:<15d}{:< 15.5f}{:< 15.5f}{:< 15.5f}'.format
    print iterPrint(0, w.value[0], w.value[1], w.value[2])
    
    for i in range(iterations):
        # Calculate gradient
        gradient = train.map(lambda p: (p.w / (1 + np.exp(-p.y * np.dot(w.value, p.x))) - 1) * p.y * np.array(p.x)).reduce(lambda a, b: a + b)
        
        # Lasso regularization
        wReg = w.value * 1
        wReg[-1] = 0 # last value of weight vector is bias term, ignored in regularization
        wReg = (wReg > 0).astype(int) * 1
        
        # Put it all together
        gradient = gradient + regParam * wReg  # gradient: GD of Sqaured Error + GD of regularized term 
        newW = w.value - learningRate * gradient / n
        wIterations.append(newW)
        print iterPrint(i + 1, newW[0], newW[1], newW[2])
        
        # Converged?
        dist = sqrt(sum([x**2 for x in (w.value - newW)]))
        if dist <= convThreshold:
            break
        
        w = sc.broadcast(newW)
        
    return wIterations

%pyspark

def plotIterations(data, weights):
    plt.clf()
    s = 9
    plt.figure(figsize=(s, s/3*2))
    
    colorDict = {1.0: '#0099ff', -1.0: '#ff5050'}
    colors = [colorDict[data[x, 2]] for x in range(len(data))]
    lineAlphas = [float(x) / (5 * len(weights)) for x in range(len(weights))]
    lineAlphas[0] = 0.5
    
    plt.scatter(data[:,0], data[:,1], c=colors, edgecolors=colors)
    plt.title("Data and all iterations\n(first iterations are transparent, then gradually become more solid)")
    
    num = 0
    for w in weights:
        x1 = [-1.5, 1.5]
        x2 = [-(w[0] * i + w[2]) / w[1] for i in x1]

        if num == 0:
            plt.plot(x1, x2, c='k', linestyle='--', alpha=lineAlphas[num], label="Initial weight")
        elif num == len(weights) - 1:
            plt.plot(x1, x2, c='b', linewidth=3, label="Final weight")
        else:
            plt.plot(x1, x2, c='k', alpha=lineAlphas[num])
        num += 1
        
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.xlim(-1.2, 1.2)
    plt.ylim(-1.2, 1.2)
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')
    
    showMPL(plt)

%pyspark

allWeights = WeightedLogRegLasso(trainData, learningRate=0.25, iterations=100, convThreshold=0.01)
print "\nConverged in", len(allWeights) - 1, "iterations"

%pyspark

def calcError(allWeights, testData):
    # We only need the last weight here
    finalWeight = sc.broadcast(allWeights[-1])
    labels = sc.broadcast({0: -1, 1: 1})
    
    correct = testData.map(lambda p: labels.value[(p.x[1] > -(finalWeight.value[0] * p.x[0] + finalWeight.value[2]) / finalWeight.value[1]).astype(int)] == p.y)
    errorRate = float(correct.filter(lambda p: p == False).count()) / testData.count()
    
    return errorRate
    
print "Misclassification:", calcError(allWeights, testData)
print "Iterations:", len(allWeights) - 1

#### 11.4.3: Derive and Implement in Spark a weighted soft linear svm classification learning algorithm.

Note: the version I implemented uses lasso (L1) regularization.

11.4.3: Derive and Implement in Spark a weighted soft linear svm classification learning algorithm.

Note: the version I implemented uses lasso (L1) regularization.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

# Get training and test data into form that we use
trainData = sc.parallelize(train).map(readPoint).cache()
testData = sc.parallelize(test).map(readPoint).cache()

%pyspark

def WeightedSoftSVM(train, learningRate=0.05, iterations=10, regParam=0.01, convThreshold=0.01):
    n = train.count()
    featureLen = len(train.take(1)[0].x)
    
    wIterations = []
    
    # Initialize weights to random
    w = sc.broadcast(np.random.normal(size=featureLen))
    wIterations.append(w.value)
    
    # Print header
    print '{:15s}{:15s}{:15s}{:15s}{:15s}'.format('iteration', 'weight[0]', 'weight[1]', 'bias', 'SVs')
    print '-'*75
    iterPrint = '{:<15d}{:< 15.5f}{:< 15.5f}{:< 15.5f}{:<15d}'.format
    print iterPrint(0, w.value[0], w.value[1], w.value[2], 0)
    
    for i in range(iterations):
        # Find support vectors
        sv = train.filter(lambda p: p.y * np.dot(w.value, p.x) < 1)
        
        if sv.isEmpty():
            break
            
        # Calculate gradient
        gradient = -sv.map(lambda p: p.w * p.y * np.array(p.x)).reduce(lambda x, y: x + y) / n
        
        # L1 regularization
        wReg = w.value * 1
        wReg[-1] = 0 # last value of weight vector is bias term, ignored in regularization
        wReg = (wReg > 0).astype(int) * 1
        
        wDelta = learningRate * (gradient + regParam * wReg)
        
        newW = w.value - wDelta
        
        wIterations.append(newW)
        print iterPrint(i + 1, newW[0], newW[1], newW[2], sv.count())
        
        # Converged?
        dist = sqrt(sum([x**2 for x in (w.value - newW)]))
        if dist <= convThreshold:
            break
        
        w = sc.broadcast(newW)
    return wIterations

%pyspark

allWeights = WeightedSoftSVM(trainData, learningRate=0.25, iterations=100, convThreshold=0.01)
print "\nConverged in", len(allWeights) - 1, "iterations"

%pyspark

plotIterations(train, allWeights)
